<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-411-964  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 411 964.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  April 1990 v27 n4 p20(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Competing in a global economy. (includes related article on US)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Adam, John A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Successful competition in the global economy is vital to ensuringemployment, national security, and living standards in Japan, WestGermany and the US.andP;  Central to competition is the production ofgoods, but this is affected by the economic conditions, researchand development (Randamp;D) support and education of the workforce.andO;Major factors in Japan's success are the heavy Randamp;D fundingprovided by the Science and Technology Agency and Ministry ofInternational Trade and Industry, lower capital costs than US orWest Germany, and higher literacy and lower dropout rates than theUS.andP;  Much of West Germany's Randamp;D funding goes to pan-Europeanprograms, but close links between banking and industry pushdevelopment, and the country's literacy and dropout rates arebetter than the US.andP;  The US leads in Randamp;D funding and itsuniversities are known for their creativity, but trade andindustrial policy is fragmented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CompetitionAnalysisUnited StatesWest GermanyJapanResearch and DevelopmentEconomicsEducationFunding.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   'Big Three' economic characteristics in 1988. (table)Technology indicators for West Germany, Japan and the US. (table)Regional shares of global production: 1980, 1988. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>